2 - Load Data

mtp <- read.csv("mtp_data.csv")

3 - Base EDA

3.1 Uni- Variate Non graphical analysis

#converting 'iri_key' and 'promo' to factors
mtp$iri_key <- as.factor(mtp$iri_key)

mtp$promo <- as.factor(mtp$promo)

#Change 0 = No, and 1 = Yes for promo
levels(mtp$promo)[1] <- "No"
levels(mtp$promo)[2] <- "Yes"

#Change a = medium, = b = small for ad
levels(mtp$ad)[1] <- "Medium"
levels(mtp$ad)[2] <- "Small"

# Create week number, revenue, qtr, and company variables
mtp$week_th <- as.integer(mtp$week - 1478)
mtp$revenue <-  (mtp$units*mtp$price)
mtp$qrt <- as.factor(sprintf("Q%s",floor(mtp$week_th/14 +1)))
mtp$company <- as.factor(substr(mtp$brand, 1,regexpr(" ", mtp$brand)-1))
levels(mtp$company)[levels(mtp$company) == "GENERAL"] <- "GENERAL MILLS"
mtp$price_vol <- (mtp$price/mtp$volume)
mtp$ad_count <- 1

# Remove UPC

mtp$UPC <- NULL

  • The data contains 21850 observations and 11 variables. (7 Factors, 2 int, 2 num)

  • The lowest price of cereal is .25 and the maximum is 9.99.

  • The two most popular flavors are Regular and Toasted.

  • The median box size (volume) is 1.060

  • Most of the cereals are distributed in box rather than cups.

  • Questions about the data:

    • Is price a coefficient of volume?

    • Is there a higher response to certain brands in regards to promotion?

    • Are flavors limited to certain brands?

    • What is the most popular flavor for each brand?

3.2 Uni-variate Graphical

3.2.1 Categorical/Factor variables

# Use histograms to graph categorical variables
grid.arrange(
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = ad)) +
  geom_bar(fill = 'slateblue')+
  theme_minimal(),
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = flavor)) +
  geom_bar(fill = 'slateblue')+
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1, size = 7)),
  
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = company)) +
  geom_bar(fill = 'slateblue')+
  theme_minimal(),
ncol = 2)

  • Most of the sales in the dataset have no ad
    • There are more medium ads than small
  • Regular is the most popular flavor, followed by Toasted
  • Kelloggs has the most frequent transactions, since the graph does not necessarily tell how many units were sold.

3.2.2 Quantitative variables

3.2.2.1 Price and Volume

grid.arrange(
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = price)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "slateblue"),
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = 1)) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y = price)) +
  coord_flip(),
  
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = volume)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "slateblue"),
  ggplot(data = mtp, mapping = aes(x = 1)) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y= volume)) +
  coord_flip()
)

  • Comments:
    • Price seems more normally distributed than volume
      • Wonder what sort of packages are selling at such a high price.
    • Most of volume runs at around 1.

    • Regular and toasted have the most promos.
    • Cinnamon toast is purchased the most during first quarter and has less promos.

5 - Statistical Analysis

5.1 Does promotion affect the amount of units sold?

mtp %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = units, fill = promo, alpha = 0.2)) +
  geom_density() +
  ggtitle("density graph for promotion")

# Boxplot to show distribution of units sold different when there's promotion by flavor
mtp %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = promo, y = units, fill = flavor)) +
  geom_boxplot()

  • Comments:
    • The means in units sold for all flavors are larger when there is a promotion.

We have found interest in finding whether there is a statistical significance between the means of average units sold when there is promos vs when there is not. With our dataset, we can construct the following hypothesis. Null Hypothesis: Promo has no influence on units sold. Average Units sold with promo equals the average units sold with no promo. Alternative Hypothesis: Promo has an influence on units sold. H0 : Mu difference = 0 H1: Mu difference not equal to zero For this analysis, we will conduct a paired T-test at alpha = .05

# t-test
t.test(mtp$units[mtp$promo == "Yes"], mtp$units[mtp$promo == "No"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mtp$units[mtp$promo == "Yes"] and mtp$units[mtp$promo == "No"]
## t = 27.59, df = 6398.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  3.070437 3.540125
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 11.196700  7.891419

Decision : Reject Ho, since the p-value is significantly small compare to alpha 0.05.

In this sample test, we concluded that there is a significant differnce in the amount of cereal purchased when there is a promotion vs when there is not. In fact, we have discovered that some flavors are more responsive to promotion. Cereal flavors including Cinnamon Toast and Toasted are the most influenced by promo, while Cocoa is has a less increase in the mean uni

5.2 Does seasonality affect units sold?

We would like to see if the means differ between each flavor per quarter. This will allow us to identify which quarter we are the strongest in sales. In order to do this we will formulate the following hypothesis:

Ho muQ1=muQ2=muQ3=muQ4 H1: All mu’s are not equal

tbl = table(mtp$qrt,mtp$flavor)
tbl
##     
##      CINNAMON TOAST COCOA FRUIT REGULAR TOASTED
##   Q1            488   442   469    2195    1770
##   Q2            530   455   564    2436    1922
##   Q3            463   597   666    2387    1841
##   Q4            353   407   493    1798    1574
chisq.test(tbl, correct = FALSE)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  tbl
## X-squared = 64.047, df = 12, p-value = 4.089e-09

At the 5% level of significance there is sufficient evidence that the proportion of units sold differ by quarter.

mtp %>% 
  group_by(flavor) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = qrt, y = units, fill = flavor)) +
  geom_boxplot()

5.3 Looking closer to our competitor pricing. Why are we losing money to Kellogs?

In our analysis, we would like to see if price per volume has a significant standpoint in the amount in revenue and units sold. We will set our alpha at .05 to initiate this thought, we will conduct a two sample t-test to see if the means between the price per volume for Kelloggs and General Mills are different.

H0 : Mu difference = 0 H1: Mu difference not equal to zero

t.test(mtp$price_vol[mtp$company == "GENERAL MILLS"], mtp$price_vol[mtp$company == "KELLOGGS"])  
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mtp$price_vol[mtp$company == "GENERAL MILLS"] and mtp$price_vol[mtp$company == "KELLOGGS"]
## t = 16.241, df = 17144, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3432175 0.4374310
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  4.529221  4.138897

Conclusion: GM price are higher than Kellogs price

Since Regular is the dominating flavor, we want to drill down this segment more deeply:

Does GM’s Regular and Kelloggs’ Regular have similar pricing?

reg_f <- subset(mtp,mtp$flavor == "REGULAR" &  mtp$company != "POST")

t.test(reg_f$price_vol[reg_f$company == "GENERAL MILLS"], reg_f$price_vol[reg_f$company == "KELLOGGS"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  reg_f$price_vol[reg_f$company == "GENERAL MILLS"] and reg_f$price_vol[reg_f$company == "KELLOGGS"]
## t = 49.529, df = 1912.3, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.672356 1.810257
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  5.017138  3.275832

Decision: We reject the null hypothesis. The different price per volume means are not equal to zero.

Conclusion: at alpha = 0.05, we state that the price per volume in Regular flavor for General Mills is significantly greater than Kelloggs. In fact, General Mills had a mean price per volume at ~$5 while Kelloggs had a mean price of $3.27.

6 - Summary

  1. For GM, Cinnamon Toast is the most popular flavor. It has a low amount of promos and ads compared to other competitors. Quarter 1 shows that Cinnamon Toast is purchased frequently even without many ads or promos. Its second popular flavor is regular, although the top revenue stores do not sell it much compared to Kelloggs.

  2. Quarter 4 shows a decline in purchases of cereals. This affects the three companies. This may be due to a switch of customer preference, although we don’t know for sure.

  3. Further tests can be done on store analysis, however more data will be needed. If we knew the store locations, we could identify patterns of flavor choices, as well as their effects on promos.

  4. It is clear Kelloggs is GM’s main competitor. GM is close at equalling in amounts of sales but behind on revenue especially with Regular flavor. One thing Kelloggs stood out for is their high count of ads and promos they do throughout the year.

  5. GM price is generally higher than Kelloggs with or without promotions, Kelloggs has higher market shares in cereals.

  6. GM should run more ads and lower our cereal price for Regular flavor.
